ical thought and practice. The contributors use Deleuze's dynamic theoretical apparatus to engage with contemporary political problems, themes and possibilities, including micropolitics, cynicism, war, democracy, ethnicity, friendship, revolution, power, fascism, militancy, and fabulation. Approaching Deleuze's politics from the disciplines of political theory, philosophy, literature, cultural studies, and sociology, the book is designed to appeal to a diverse audience.The essays in this volume focus on three key issuesThe ontology of Deleuze's political philosophyThe philosophical debate between Deleuze and contemporary critical theoryThe application of Deleuze's political philosophy to real-world events"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aBuchanan, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColebrook, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeLanda, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaro, Isabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, Eugene W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrause, Ralf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, Gregg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMengue, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatton, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRead, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRölli, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThoburn, Nicholas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aThoburn, Ni